`,(0,t.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["If you haven\u2019t heard of it, Ion is the ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://sst.dev/blog/moving-away-from-cdk.html#what-is-ion",children:"upcoming v3"})," of ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://sst.dev/",children:"SST"}),", and it\u2019s quite the Swiss Army knife of deployment tools. This is especially so with the switch from AWS ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://aws.amazon.com/cdk/",children:"CDK"}),"/",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://aws.amazon.com/cloudformation/",children:"CFN"})," to ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://www.pulumi.com/",children:"Pulumi"})," & ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://www.terraform.io/",children:"Terraform"})," providers to handle your Infrastructure as Code (IaC). In my use case, I used Ion\u2019s ",(0,t.jsxs)(e.a,{href:"https://ion.sst.dev/docs/component/aws/nextjs/",children:[(0,t.jsx)(e.code,{children:"Nextjs"})," component"]})," which does a few very handy things in addition to some Next.js specific IaC which we\u2019ll get to later."]}),`
`,(0,t.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["Now, the main reason for rebuilding my personal site was simply because it no longer reflected my current skill set. Unlike the site you\u2019re reading this on, my old site\u2014nothing fancy, just a ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://www.gatsbyjs.com/",children:"Gatsby"})," frontend on ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://aws.amazon.com/amplify/",children:"Amplify"}),"\u2014from a few years back was much less ",(0,t.jsx)(e.em,{children:"refined"}),". So, I decided to wipe the slate clean, but I had some goals in mind. I wanted this website to be modern, yet ",(0,t.jsx)(e.em,{children:"ambitious"}),", with an accompanying codebase that was flexible (read: organized) enough for me to feed my lust for cutting-edge technologies for years to come."]}),`
`,(0,t.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["While the latter condition was solved by simply setting this site up in a monorepo (I used ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://turbo.build/",children:"Turborepo"})," for that), everything else meant becoming quite adventurous with this project\u2019s stack. I specifically chose technologies that would push me well beyond my comfort zone to both learn and to integrate. That ultimately meant leaving the ease and familiarity of ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://svelte.dev/",children:"Svelte"})," and ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://kit.svelte.dev/",children:"SvelteKit"})," to build this site with tools I\u2019d once found overcomplicated and confusing\u2014React and Next.js."]}),`
`,(0,t.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["Likewise, it also meant learning a subfield of programming that I was once wholly intimidated by, graphics. In effect, I used ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://threejs.org/",children:"Three.js"}),", ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://docs.pmnd.rs/react-three-fiber/getting-started/introduction",children:"React Three Fiber"}),", and even some ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://www.khronos.org/opengl/wiki/Core_Language_(GLSL)",children:"GLSL"})," to add some fun WebGL-flare. This can be seen in the shader on the landing page, and also ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"/projects/bot-clicker",children:"this mini-game"})," that almost became such a page. I also happened to stumble upon ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://zustand-demo.pmnd.rs/",children:"Zustand"}),", a lightweight state management system for React, which integrated with the latter very well."]}),`
`,(0,t.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["Furthermore, I even abandoned the various headless CMSes I\u2019ve grown comfortable with over the years, in favor of something I can call my own. In effect, I wrote a prebuild script to assemble my ",(0,t.jsx)(e.em,{children:"data layer"})," which takes advantage of ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://bun.sh/",children:"Bun"}),"\u2019s speedy ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://bun.sh/docs/api/file-io",children:"File I/O API"})," to find and process MDX files with ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://github.com/jonschlinkert/gray-matter",children:"gray-matter"}),"\u2014and any contained featured images with ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://plaiceholder.co/docs",children:"plaiceholder"}),"\u2014saving the resultant array of objects into a SQLite-ish (",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://github.com/tursodatabase/libsql",children:"libSQL"}),") database on ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://turso.tech/",children:"Turso"})," via ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://orm.drizzle.team/",children:"Drizzle ORM"})," statements. I then fetch that data inside a server component to render it out in various ways, such as with ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://github.com/kentcdodds/mdx-bundler",children:(0,t.jsx)(e.code,{children:"mdx-bundler"})}),"."]}),`
`,(0,t.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["I also wrote another prebuild script for the ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"/feed.xml",children:"blog\u2019s web feed"}),". That one fetches the blog posts, and integrates them into a purpose built object which is turned into an XML string with ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://github.com/davidcalhoun/jstoxml",children:(0,t.jsx)(e.code,{children:"jstoxml"})}),". While I\u2019d like to talk about this data layer portion further, it is, admittedly, a bit extensive. So, you\u2019ll have to wait to read about in a later blog post."]}),`
`,(0,t.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["Beyond that, I\u2019m overall really happy with how everything turned out. While Next.js and Ion/SST aren\u2019t without their flaws\u2014something not too unexpected of bleeding-edge tools\u2014the pairing still came together quite nicely (in tandem with everything else) to create something I\u2019m quite proud of. Even if there\u2019s still bugs (read: mistakes) I\u2019d like to fix in the ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://github.com/laniakita/website/tree/master/apps/laniakita-web",children:"codebase"}),", the end result works like it should for the most part. Page load times are quite fast. Its Lighthouse scores are decent enough (admittedly, I\u2019m sure there\u2019s still more I could do to improve accessibility). There\u2019s all plenty of room for me to grow and build on top of it. As such, I don\u2019t regret developing this site with Next.js or shipping it with Ion/SST at all!"]}),`
