`,(0,t.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["I should mention however, that streaming isn\u2019t a configuration constant, or a special component like the App router\u2019s instant fallback ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://nextjs.org/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/loading",children:"loading UI"})," feature. Streaming is instead, a server-side rendering pattern that can be implemented on SSR pages ",(0,t.jsx)(e.em,{children:"only"}),"."]}),`
`,(0,t.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["When implemented properly, streaming results in progressively sending components over to the client browser from fastest to slowest fetch request payload. This is done by simply wrapping each component found on such an SSR page with a ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://react.dev/reference/react/Suspense",children:(0,t.jsx)(e.code,{children:"<Suspense />"})})," boundary."]}),`
`,(0,t.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["In effect, components that don\u2019t fetch any data will load first, while components that do, will ",(0,t.jsx)(e.em,{children:"stream-in"})," to the client browser in the order it takes to complete their respective fetch requests. As such, streaming creates a better browsing experience as the page won\u2019t feel ",(0,t.jsx)(e.em,{children:"stuck"})," as it loads in. Well, given you can ship enough of the UI for it to feel that way, but I digress."]}),`
`,(0,t.jsxs)(e.p,{children:["While these blog posts aren\u2019t SSR yet\u2014ergo no streaming\u2014I\u2019ve prepared these post pages to do exactly that in using ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://github.com/kentcdodds/mdx-bundler",children:(0,t.jsx)(e.code,{children:"mdx-bundler"})}),". It relies on ",(0,t.jsx)(e.a,{href:"https://esbuild.github.io/getting-started/#bundling-for-the-browser",children:"esbuild"})," to render ",(0,t.jsx)(e.code,{children:"mdx"})," strings live in production. As such, it really won\u2019t be difficult to implement the streaming rendering pattern when I do. Especially since I already invested in the App router."]}),`
